===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{Han compound|一|皿|t1=drop of blood|t2=container|ls=ic}} - a drop of blood inside a [[chalice]] for sacrificial uses. In the oracle bone script, the character was used to refer to killing animals to obtain blood to sacrifice to ancestors:<ref>{{R:yue:Hanzi}}</ref>
{{zh-x|血 三 羊。|to '''(ritually) bleed''' three sheep|CL-PC|collapsed=y|ref=''{{w|Jiaguwen Heji}}'' #22231}}
{{zh-x|在\才{zài}  血 室|to be in the '''blood (sacrifice)''' hall|CL-PC|collapsed=y|ref=''{{w|Jiaguwen Heji}}'' #41091}}

===Etymology===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s-hjwəj-t||blood}} (STEDT; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

{{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart (2014)}} reconstruct the {{cog|och|-}} as {{m|und|*m̥ˤik}} to account for word-family connections with {{och-l|脈|tr=*C.mˤ<r>[i]k|vein}}, {{och-l|衊|tr=*mˤi[k]|defiled blood}} as well as its use as a phonetic component in {{och-l|侐|tr=*m̥(r)ik|still; quiet}}, which is in the same word family as {{och-l|宓|tr=*mi[k]|quiet; silent}} ({{zh-ref|Sagart, 1999b}}; {{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart, 2017}}). {{zh-ref|Sagart (1999b)}} argues that this word is not genetically related to the {{cog|tbq}} form with ''*s-hjw-'', but that this word has been borrowed into {{cog|tbq}}. 

{{zh-ref|Schuessler (2019)}} critiques {{zh-ref|Sagart (1999b)}}'s proposal that Tibeto-Burman languages all over Southeast Asia and the Himalayas in early dynastic time would and could borrow Chinese words, and {{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart (2014)}}'s reconstruction {{och-l|血|tr= {{IPAfont|*m̥ˤik}}}} as resulting from "phonetic over-interpretation of graphs" and confusing etymological link with mental association between "blood" and "vein".

